{ id:125, year:2025, microtheme:"Environmental Issues & Current Affairs", subtheme:"Wet Bulb Temperature",
  question:"The World Bank warned about wet-bulb temperatures exceeding 35°C in India. Which implication is correct?\n1. Peninsular India will suffer flooding, cyclones and droughts.\n2. Survival of animals including humans will be affected as perspiration-based heat shedding becomes difficult.",
  options:{ a:"1 only", b:"2 only", c:"Both 1 and 2", d:"Neither 1 nor 2" }, answer:"b",
  explanation:"At 35°C wet-bulb, the body cannot cool through sweating — a survival limit (2 correct). Statement 1 describes general climate impacts, not specific wet-bulb implications." },

{ id:126, year:2025, microtheme:"Environmental Issues & Current Affairs", subtheme:"Cloud Seeding",
  question:"Artificial rainfall to reduce air pollution uses:",
  options:{ a:"Silver iodide and potassium iodide", b:"Silver nitrate and potassium iodide", c:"Silver iodide and potassium nitrate", d:"Silver nitrate and potassium chloride" }, answer:"a",
  explanation:"Cloud seeding uses silver iodide (AgI) and potassium iodide (KI) as cloud condensation nuclei." },

{ id:127, year:2025, microtheme:"Environmental Issues & Current Affairs", subtheme:"Cement Emissions",
  question:"Consider the following:\nStatement-I: Cement industry accounts for more than 5% of global CO₂ emissions.\nStatement-II: Silica-bearing clay is mixed with limestone in cement manufacturing.\nStatement-III: Limestone is converted into lime during clinker production.\nWhich one of the following is correct?",
  options:{ a:"Both II and III correct and both explain I", b:"Both II and III correct but only one explains I", c:"Only one of II and III is correct", d:"Neither II nor III is correct" }, answer:"b",
  explanation:"Both II and III are correct, but only III directly explains CO₂ emissions — limestone calcination (CaCO₃ → CaO + CO₂) is the main source of cement emissions." },

{ id:128, year:2019, microtheme:"Environmental Issues & Current Affairs", subtheme:"Pyrolysis",
  question:"'Pyrolysis and Plasma Gasification' are mentioned in the context of:",
  options:{ a:"Extraction of rare earth elements", b:"Natural gas extraction", c:"Hydrogen fuel automobiles", d:"Waste-to-energy technologies" }, answer:"d",
  explanation:"Pyrolysis and plasma gasification are waste-to-energy technologies converting waste into energy and fuels." },

{ id:129, year:2019, microtheme:"Environmental Issues & Current Affairs", subtheme:"Himalayan Nettle",
  question:"Himalayan nettle (Girardinia diversifolia) is a sustainable source of:",
  options:{ a:"Anti-malarial drug", b:"Biodiesel", c:"Pulp for paper", d:"Textile fibre" }, answer:"d",
  explanation:"Himalayan nettle yields strong, durable natural fibres used for ropes, mats, bags, and clothing." },

{ id:130, year:2016, microtheme:"Environmental Issues & Current Affairs", subtheme:"Kharai Camel",
  question:"Unique features of Kharai camel:\n1. Swims up to three km in seawater.\n2. Survives by grazing on mangroves.\n3. Lives wild and cannot be domesticated.",
  options:{ a:"1 and 2 only", b:"3 only", c:"1 and 3 only", d:"1, 2 and 3" }, answer:"a",
  explanation:"Kharai camels swim up to 3 km in seawater (1 correct) and feed on mangrove leaves (2 correct). They are domesticated by local communities (3 incorrect)." },

{ id:131, year:2015, microtheme:"Environmental Issues & Current Affairs", subtheme:"Fly Ash",
  question:"With reference to 'fly ash' from coal power plants:\n1. It can be used in production of bricks.\n2. It can replace some Portland cement in concrete.\n3. It contains only silicon dioxide and calcium oxide — no toxic elements.",
  options:{ a:"1 and 2 only", b:"2 only", c:"1 and 3 only", d:"3 only" }, answer:"a",
  explanation:"Fly ash bricks (1 correct) and pozzolanic cement additive (2 correct). It contains toxic elements like arsenic, mercury, and heavy metals (3 incorrect)." },

{ id:132, year:2015, microtheme:"Environmental Issues & Current Affairs", subtheme:"Fuel Cells",
  question:"About fuel cells using hydrogen and oxygen:\n1. If pure hydrogen is used, by-products are heat and water.\n2. Cannot power small devices like laptops.\n3. Produce AC electricity.",
  options:{ a:"1 only", b:"2 and 3 only", c:"1 and 3 only", d:"1, 2 and 3" }, answer:"a",
  explanation:"Pure hydrogen fuel cells emit only heat and water (1 correct). Fuel cells are scalable — can power laptops to buildings (2 incorrect). They produce DC, not AC (3 incorrect)." },

{ id:133, year:2014, microtheme:"Environmental Issues & Current Affairs", subtheme:"Temperature Rise Impacts",
  question:"If global temperature rises by just 1°C above pre-industrial levels:\n1. Terrestrial biosphere tends toward a net carbon source.\n2. Widespread coral mortality will occur.\n3. All global wetlands will permanently disappear.\n4. Cereal cultivation will be impossible anywhere.",
  options:{ a:"1 only", b:"1 and 2 only", c:"2, 3 and 4 only", d:"1, 2, 3 and 4" }, answer:"b",
  explanation:"Terrestrial ecosystems shift toward being net carbon sources (1 correct). Coral mortality increases significantly (2 correct). Wetlands won't all disappear (3 incorrect). Cereals will still grow (4 incorrect)." },

{ id:134, year:2013, microtheme:"Environmental Issues & Current Affairs", subtheme:"Contour Bunding",
  question:"Contour bunding is a method of soil conservation used in:",
  options:{ a:"Desert margins liable to strong wind action", b:"Low flat plains close to streams liable to flooding", c:"Scrublands liable to weed growth", d:"None of the above" }, answer:"d",
  explanation:"Contour bunding is used on sloping terrain (hill slopes) to prevent water erosion. None of the listed options describe such terrain." },

{ id:135, year:2013, microtheme:"Environmental Issues & Current Affairs", subtheme:"Water Industry",
  question:"Which industry is the maximum consumer of water in India?",
  options:{ a:"Engineering", b:"Paper and pulp", c:"Textiles", d:"Thermal power" }, answer:"d",
  explanation:"Thermal power plants use enormous quantities of water for cooling, making them the largest industrial water consumers in India." }

